from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder

columns_failure_type = data['Failure Type'].unique().tolist()

# Pass on the categorical values
ord_enc = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['L', 'M', 'H'], columns_failure_type])

# Fit and transform the data for feature 'Type' and target 'Failure Type'
new_data = ord_enc.fit_transform(data[['Type', 'Failure Type']])
new_data
data.drop(['Type', 'Failure Type'], axis=1, inplace=True)

new_df = pd.DataFrame(new_data,
                      index=data.index,
                      columns=['Type', 'Failure Type'])

data_enc = pd.concat([data, new_df], axis=1)
data_enc = data_enc.reset_index(drop=True)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split


X = data_scaled.drop(['Target', 'Failure Type'], axis=1)
y = data_scaled['Target']


# setting up testing and training sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=0)

print(X_test.shape)

(2494, 6)
In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score,f1_score,recall_score
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, BaggingClassifier,GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV


models = [
        LogisticRegression(),
        RandomForestClassifier(),
        BaggingClassifier(),
        SVC(kernel='linear'),
        GradientBoostingClassifier(),
        KNeighborsClassifier()
    ]

# Define the parameter grids for each model
param_grids = [
    {'C': [0.1, 1, 10], 'penalty': ['l1', 'l2']},
    {'n_estimators': [50, 100, 150], 'max_depth': [5, 10, 15]},
    {'n_estimators': [50, 100, 150]},
    {'C': [0.1, 1, 10]},
    {'n_estimators': [50, 100, 150], 'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.5, 1.0]},
    {'n_neighbors': [3, 5, 7]}
]
# Initialize empty lists to store results
model_names = []
best_params_list = []
accuracy_list = []
f1_list = []
recall_list = []

# Iterate over the models and parameter grids, and fit the GridSearchCV object to the training data
for model, param_grid in zip(models, param_grids):
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5)
    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
    model_name = model.__class__.__name__
    model_names.append(model_name)
    best_params = grid_search.best_params_
    best_params_list.append(best_params)

    # Predict the labels of the test data using the optimal parameters
    y_pred = grid_search.predict(X_test)

    # Evaluate the performance of the classifier using accuracy score, F1 score, and recall
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro')
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro')

    # Append the results to the lists
    accuracy_list.append(accuracy)
    f1_list.append(f1)
    recall_list.append(recall)

# Create a pandas dataframe to store the results
results_df = pd.DataFrame({'Model': model_names, 'Best Parameters': best_params_list, 'Accuracy': accuracy_list, 'F1 Score': f1_list, 'Recall': recall_list})
print(results_df)

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, precision_recall_curve, auc

# Import necessary libraries
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, precision_recall_curve, auc

# Define a function to plot ROC and Precision-Recall curves
def roc_prec_recall_curves(model):
    fig, axList = plt.subplots(ncols=2)
    fig.set_size_inches(16, 8)

    # Check if the model has the predict_proba method
    if hasattr(model, 'predict_proba'):
        y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    else:
        y_prob = model.decision_function(X_test)
        y_prob = (y_prob - y_prob.min()) / (y_prob.max() - y_prob.min())

    # ROC curve
    ax = axList[0]
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
    ax.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=5)
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], ls='--', color='black', lw=.3)
    ax.set(xlabel='False Positive Rate',
           ylabel='True Positive Rate',
           xlim=[-.01, 1.01], ylim=[-.01, 1.01],
           title='ROC curve')
    ax.grid(True)

    # Precision-Recall curve
    ax = axList[1]
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_prob)
    ax.plot(recall, precision, linewidth=5)
    ax.set(xlabel='Recall', ylabel='Precision',
           xlim=[-.01, 1.01], ylim=[-.01, 1.01],
           title='Precision-Recall curve')
    ax.grid(True)

    plt.suptitle(str(model).split('(')[0])
    plt.show()

# Iterate over the models and plot ROC and Precision-Recall curves
for model in models:
    roc_prec_recall_curves(model)

import dash
import dash_core_components as dcc
import dash_html_components as html
import pandas as pd
import plotly.graph_objects as go



# Effectuer les prétraitements nécessaires

# Définir les modèles et les techniques d'échantillonnage
models = {

    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(learning_rate=0.1, n_estimators=150),
    "K-Nearest Neighbors": KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
}

samplers = {
    "Oversampling": SMOTE(),
    "Undersampling": TomekLinks(),
    # Ajoutez d'autres techniques d'échantillonnage si nécessaire
}

# Créer l'application Dash
app = dash.Dash(__name__)

# Créer une fonction pour générer les matrices de confusion
def generate_confusion_matrix(model, sampler):
    X = data.drop("Target", axis=1)  # Les caractéristiques
    y = data["Target"]  # La variable cible

    X_resampled, y_resampled = sampler.fit_resample(X, y)

    model.fit(X_resampled, y_resampled)
    y_pred = model.predict(X)

    labels = sorted(data["Target"].unique())
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred, labels=labels)
    report = classification_report(y, y_pred, labels=labels)

    return cm, report

# Créer la mise en page de l'application Dash
app.layout = html.Div(
    children=[
        html.H1("Visualisation des composants du modèle de maintenance prédictive"),
        html.H2("Modèles groupés par technique d'échantillonnage"),
    ]
)

# Générer les matrices de confusion et les rapports de classification pour chaque modèle et technique d'échantillonnage
for model_name, model in models.items():
    for sampler_name, sampler in samplers.items():
        cm, report = generate_confusion_matrix(model, sampler)

        # Ajouter la matrice de confusion au layout
        fig = go.Figure(data=go.Heatmap(z=cm, x=labels, y=labels, colorscale="RdBu", showscale=True))
        fig.update_layout(title=f"Matrice de confusion | Modèle: {model_name} | Technique d'échantillonnage: {sampler_name}")
        confusion_matrix_graph = dcc.Graph(figure=fig)

        # Ajouter le rapport de classification au layout
        classification_report_text = html.Pre(report)

        # Ajouter le tableau des résultats au layout
        result_table = pd.DataFrame(
            {
                "Métrique": ["F1 Score", "Recall", "Accuracy"],
                "Score": [
                    classification_report_dict["weighted avg"]["f1-score"],
                    classification_report_dict["weighted avg"]["recall"],
                    classification_report_dict["accuracy"],
                ],
            }
        )
        result_table_html = html.Table(
            [html.Tr([html.Th(col) for col in result_table.columns])] +
            [html.Tr([html.Td(data) for data in row]) for row in result_table.values.tolist()]
        )

        app.layout.children.append(html.H3(f"Modèle: {model_name} | Technique d'échantillonnage: {sampler_name}"))
        app.layout.children.append(html.H4("Matrice de confusion"))

        app.layout.children.append(classification_report_text)
        app.layout.children.append(html.H4("Tableau des résultats"))
        app.layout.children.append(result_table_html)
